That fact alone tells you that the Verge doesn't consider Samsung events or flagship phones very important, or at least worthy enough to have their best staff cover it. Generally speaking, Samsung stories on the Verge are usually highly critical and written to portray Samsung in a negative light while their Apple stories are normally full of praise and written to show Apple in a favorable light. And if you don't believe me, just listen to their one of their podcast. Nilay and Dieter Bohn are constantly trashing Samsung. \n\nBut hey, that's perfectly fine!! Actually, I have no problem with any tech site giving Apple favorable treatment. No more invitations to Apple events. No more advance review phones. No more soup for you! Since Apple Keynotes are the Super Bowl of tech events, it would be absolutely stupid from a business standpoint to do anything whatsoever that might be offensive to Apple. "WHY APPLE WINS AND REVIEWERS LOSE:

iPhone XS & XS Max AREN'T for people who already use an 'iPhone X'. They are, as is the case with every new iPhone, aimed at people coming from OLDER iPhones (such as 7, 6s or even 5s/5). 

The idea that Apple makes iPhones ONLY for those who bought last year's iPhone is INSANE. You don't buy an iPhone every year (!) unless you are a famous Youtuber or are filthy rich. 

MOST people that buy one use their iPhone for AT LEAST 2-3 years (some for '5' years, even) before upgrading. Unlike Android flagships, iPhones are traditionally extremely future-proof: the '5S', which released all the way back in *2013*, is STILL getting software updates & running smooth as butter in '2018'.

So.. The industry-first '7 nm processor', the '8-core ML neural engine', the crazy-powerful GPU & ALL the other super hardware upgrades that might seem 'overkill' today are actually there, IRONICALLY enough, so 'people WON'T need to buy a new iPhone for the next few years'..  

Reviewers always fail to take all that into account & end up judging the latest iPhone purely in relation to how it stacks up against its immediate predecessor: So they simply quote the '15%' jump in this and '30%' boost in that. They don't see the '300%' jump that someone coming from a 5S or 6 would experience. Shallow A....F.

While long-time customers, aka the MAJORITY of iPhone buyers, understand Apple's long-term approach & ignore these reviews. 

Which is precisely why iPhone sales are NEVER affected by reviews, however negative or even positive they might be. Cuz for the most part, they're 'unrelatable'."

"WHY APPLE WINS AND REVIEWERS LOSE:

iPhone XS & XS Max AREN'T for people who *already* use an 'iPhone X'. They are, as is the case with every new iPhone, aimed at people coming from OLDER iPhones (such as 7, 6s or even 5s/5). 

The idea that Apple makes iPhones ONLY for those who bought *last year's* iPhone is INSANE. You don't buy an iPhone *every year* (!) unless you are a famous Youtuber or are filthy rich. 

MOST people that buy one use their iPhone for AT LEAST 2-3 years (some for '5' years, even) before upgrading. Unlike Android flagships, iPhones are traditionally extremely future-proof: the '5S', which released all the way back in *2013*, is STILL getting software updates & running smooth as butter in '2018'.

So.. The industry-first '7 nm processor', the '8-core ML neural engine', the crazy-powerful GPU & ALL the other super hardware upgrades that might seem 'overkill' *today* are actually there, IRONICALLY enough, so 'people WON'T need to buy a new iPhone for the next few years'..  

Reviewers always fail to take all that into account & end up judging the latest iPhone *purely* in relation to how it stacks up against its immediate predecessor: So they simply quote the '15%' jump in this and '30%' boost in that. They don't see the '300%' jump that someone coming from a 5S or 6 would experience. Shallow AH.

While long-time customers, aka the MAJORITY of iPhone buyers, understand Apple's long-term approach & ignore these reviews. 

Which is *precisely* why iPhone sales are NEVER affected by reviews, however negative or even positive they might be. Cuz for the most part, they're 'unrelatable'."

"I'm a Note kind of guy.  I've had nothing but Notes since the very first one.  But I'm an honest kind of guy.  I asked myself a simple question.  Which phone would I want in my pocket in an emergency situation.  It takes me no time to blurt out, iPhone.  Of all the phones and all the products and all the tech companies out there, Apple is the one that I actually trust to deliver something that works well, the vast majority of the time.  Apple makes products that do something that no other products have done for me.  They exceed my expectation.  You might wonder, if I hold Apple with such high regard then why am I not using an iPhone and have never owned one.  The answer is simply that I don't like Apple's barebones approach to most of their products.  While the Note has comically garbage software in it like Bixby, the mess that preceeded Bixby (LOL), the Samsung Health app which is as comical as Bixby of course, and other stuff that kinda sorta works, it does have a lot of stuff in there that I actually want and use all the time.  And Samsung has those things, exclusively.  iPhone doesn't begin to try to make a mobile device to empower the consumer.  However.  The iPhone is more likely to save my life if I went, \"Cough, cough, \"hey Bixby (or Siri)....cough, cough....dial 911....\"  Bixby would probably go.....\"OK, navigating to Dunkin Donuts....you've reached level 1075 Bixby points\".  Siri on the other hand would probably hear me coughing and go...\"I-hear-you-coughing....Should-I-Call-911?\"  I don't think that's an exaggeration.  That's the advice that Bixby gave me, twice, when I asked, what is the fastest car in the world.  The answer...Here's Dunkin Donuts on the map."

"If you've got the money to buy it outright (without financing/debt trap) or you are a person that also uses a Mac computer / iPad Pro heavily then it makes sense to get the iPhone. 

But if you are a regular Joe who uses your smartphone for calls, msgs, YouTube, online shopping, YouTube, casual web browsing and for some casual photos, them you are better off buying a smartphone for under $200 

A regular Joe has to keep in mind that no matter which phone you buy (the most expensive iPhone or a budget Android phone), they all slowly lose their battery efficiency and speed, after 1 year of use. So, if you buy a $200 phone, use it for a year, then sell it off for $100, you just need to add another $100 max to buy the latest smartphone with newer specs and newer software right out of the box. Plus you don't need to use your credit card or financing a $1000 phone and get into debt trap and still get to use a a very efficient and latest smartphone."
